their kids to college. However, these dreams of upward mobility are often dashed by the difficulty of trying to get by on meager wages. In accessible and engaging prose, It’s Not Like I’m Poor examines the costs and benefits of the new work-based safety net, suggesting ways to augment its strengths so that more of the working poor can realize the promise of a middle-class life.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aPublic welfarexHistoryx20th centuryxUnited States. 0aPublic welfarezUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aTax creditsxUnited StatesxUnited States. 0aTax creditszUnited States. 0aWorking poorxHistoryx20th centuryxUnited States. 0aWorking poorzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / General.2bisacsh1 aEdin, Kathryn, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aTach, Laura, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete Package 2014-2015z978311062111240uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052095922440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520959224423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520959224/original  a978-3-11-062111-2  University of California Press Complete Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles